<div class="mt-4 mb-3">
    <p class="font-weight-bold">What is Alzheimer's disease?</p>
    <p>
        Alzheimer's disease for the first time has been described in 1906 by German neuropathologist Alois Altsgejmer.
        Alzheimer's disease is the most widespread reason of dementia. Under the term "dementia" various progressing degenerative
        brain syndromes which amaze memory, thinking, behavior and emotions are incorporated. Characteristic for dementia is:
    </p>
    <ul>
        <li>Loss of memory,</li>
        <li>Difficulties in a presence of correct words or in understanding of that other people speak,</li>
        <li>Difficulties in performance routine has put</li>
        <li>Changes in mood and personal qualities.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
        Dementia is not a normal component of ageing. It does not know neither social, nor economic, ethnic or geographical borders.
        Usually it is shown after 40-50 years, but earlier display of disease has been registered in 28 years. Though at each person
        it is in own way shown dementia, however all these patients are not capable to care of themselves and require the everyday constant help.
    </p>
    <p>
        For diagnostics of Alzheimer's disease while there is no test with which help probably correctly to diagnose. Therefore the doctor should
        exclude all those diseases which result in development of dementia symptoms. Especially those diseases which are exposed to treatment:
        infections, traumas, tumors, mental infringements. Even at exception of other diseases diagnostics of Alzheimer's disease remains suspected.
        Authentic diagnostics is possible only microscopic research which is usually carried out after death. Sometimes the given research is carried
        out among alive people for what take small tests of a brain fabric.
    </p>
    <p>
        Alzheimer's disease is intensively studied all over the world, however will pass a lot of time before its final treatment will be found.
        Therefore patients with dementia and their trustees require the constant practical help and support.
    </p>
    <p>
        Today more than 35 million people worldwide have dementia and those numbers will double every 20 years to 65,7 million in 2030 and 115,4
        million in 2050, according to the World Alzheimer’s Report from Alzheimer’s Disease International.
    </p>
    <p>
        According to the international statistics in Armenia it should be totaled approximately 30 thousand patients with dementia.
    </p>
